Quite apart from her singing, she was much in the news in the Spring of 1916, becaus eher husband was arrested and charged with plotting to blow up the Welland Canal.  See, for example, the NYT of March 31, 1916
  select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10E13FE3A5B17738DDDA80B94DB405B868DF1D3
&quot;GADSKI'S HUSBAND ARRESTED IN PLOT TO BLOW UP CANAL; Capt. Tauscher, Krupp Agent, Seized as Conspirator to Wreck Welland Waterway. DATES BACK TO AUGUST, '14 Von der Goltz Gave Evidence Involving von Papen, Which Led to Capture. RAID THROUGH PRIVATE DOOR Government Holds Him in $25,000 Bail -- Admits Activity, but Denies the Charge. GADSKI'S HUSBAND ARRESTED IN PLOT&quot;

This photo appeared in The Sunday Oregonian, March 26, 1916, SECTION FIVE, Image 71 with the caption:
&quot;Alexander Blair Thaw is a brother of William Thaw, who is with the French army aviation corps. Alexander is an aviator also. Recently he was trying to fly to Governor's Island, when his engine went wrong, and he was obliged to make a perilous descent in Central Park, where his machine was wrecked. The aviator and his me chanic escaped unhurt.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1916-03-26/ed-1/seq-71/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1916-03-26/ed-1/se...</a>

LOC: Caption should be &quot;Thaw&quot;, not &quot;Pan&quot;

This is the airplane of Alexander B. Thaw, a civilian pilot who crash-landed his plane in Central Park on March 6, 1916 after running out of gas during a trip from Hempstead, Long Island to Governor's Island. The wings were damaged in the crash.  I'm guessing this photo was taken after the wings and propeller were removed so the plane could be towed away.
<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9B06E0D8103FE233A25754C0A9659C946796D6CF" rel="nofollow">query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9B06E0D8103FE2...</a>

